        <title>ants on turntable (speed)</title>
        <contents>&lt;p&gt;Two ants are standing still on a turntable (in case you don't know, a turntable is an ancient device used to play "records" which were an audio recording format used in antiquity). The turntable is turning. Ant A is 1.0 cm from the center of the turntable. Ant B is 5.0 cm from the center of the turntable. Which ant has the greater speed?&lt;/p&gt;</contents>
        <contentsformat>1</contentsformat>
        <answers>
          <answer id="21770">
            <jumpto>9523</jumpto>
            <grade>0</grade>
            <score>1</score>
            <flags>0</flags>
            <timecreated>1469463873</timecreated>
            <timemodified>0</timemodified>
            <answer_text>Ant B</answer_text>
            <response>Yes.  Both ants complete a "trip around the circle" in the same amount of time.  Ant B travels further in that time so it is going faster.</response>
            <answerformat>0</answerformat>
            <responseformat>0</responseformat>
            <attempts>
            </attempts>
          </answer>
          <answer id="21771">
            <jumpto>-80</jumpto>
            <grade>0</grade>
            <score>0</score>
            <flags>0</flags>
            <timecreated>1469463873</timecreated>
            <timemodified>0</timemodified>
            <answer_text>Ant A</answer_text>
            <response>No.  Both ants complete a "trip around the circle" in the same amount of time (the same amount of time it takes for the turntable to go around once).  Ant B travels further in that time because it is going around a larger circle, so it is going faster.</response>
            <answerformat>0</answerformat>
            <responseformat>0</responseformat>
            <attempts>
            </attempts>
          </answer>
          <answer id="21772">
            <jumpto>-80</jumpto>
            <grade>0</grade>
            <score>0</score>
            <flags>0</flags>
            <timecreated>1469463873</timecreated>
            <timemodified>0</timemodified>
            <answer_text>The ants are moving at the same speed.</answer_text>
            <response>No.  Both ants complete a "trip around the circle" in the same amount of time (the same amount of time it takes for the turntable to go around once).  So their *periods* are the same.  But the question asked about speed, not period.  Ant B travels further in that time because it is going around a larger circle, so it is going faster.</response>
            <answerformat>0</answerformat>
            <responseformat>0</responseformat>
            <attempts>
            </attempts>
          </answer>
          <answer id="21773">
            <jumpto>-80</jumpto>
            <grade>0</grade>
            <score>0</score>
            <flags>0</flags>
            <timecreated>1469463873</timecreated>
            <timemodified>0</timemodified>
            <answer_text>Both ants are stationary (speed 0).</answer_text>
            <response>Relative to the turntable they are stationary.  But if you were on a merry go round which was turning I doubt you would describe yourself as stationary.  We are talking about the ants' speeds relative to the ground, which is certainly not zero.</response>
            <answerformat>0</answerformat>
            <responseformat>0</responseformat>
            <attempts>
            </attempts>
          </answer>
