        <title>direction of net force on person in roller coaster</title>
        <contents>&lt;p&gt;You are riding a roller coaster which has a loop. At the instant that you pass through the top of the loop which way is the net force on you?&lt;/p&gt;</contents>
        <contentsformat>1</contentsformat>
        <answers>
          <answer id="21775">
            <jumpto>9534</jumpto>
            <grade>0</grade>
            <score>1</score>
            <flags>0</flags>
            <timecreated>1469479240</timecreated>
            <timemodified>0</timemodified>
            <answer_text>down</answer_text>
            <response>Yes, since down is towards the centre of the circle you are moving in.</response>
            <answerformat>0</answerformat>
            <responseformat>0</responseformat>
            <attempts>
            </attempts>
          </answer>
          <answer id="21776">
            <jumpto>-80</jumpto>
            <grade>0</grade>
            <score>0</score>
            <flags>0</flags>
            <timecreated>1469479240</timecreated>
            <timemodified>0</timemodified>
            <answer_text>up</answer_text>
            <response>No.  This is uniform circular motion (just like the car at the bottom of the valley in the lecture).  At the top of the loop the centre of the circle is below you.  So the net force is down.</response>
            <answerformat>0</answerformat>
            <responseformat>0</responseformat>
            <attempts>
            </attempts>
          </answer>
          <answer id="21777">
            <jumpto>-80</jumpto>
            <grade>0</grade>
            <score>0</score>
            <flags>0</flags>
            <timecreated>1469479240</timecreated>
            <timemodified>0</timemodified>
            <answer_text>forward (i.e. in the direction of your motion)</answer_text>
            <response>No, you may have a persistent confusion between velocity and acceleration.  We have seen (draw the motion diagram) that in uniform circular motion the acceleration points toward the centre of the circle.  Newton's 2nd Law tells us that the net force acts in the same direction as the acceleration.  So the net force acts down since that is the direction to the centre of the circle.</response>
            <answerformat>0</answerformat>
            <responseformat>0</responseformat>
            <attempts>
            </attempts>
          </answer>
          <answer id="21778">
            <jumpto>-80</jumpto>
            <grade>0</grade>
            <score>0</score>
            <flags>0</flags>
            <timecreated>1469479240</timecreated>
            <timemodified>0</timemodified>
            <answer_text>zero</answer_text>
            <response>No.  Are you thinking that the speed is constant so the acceleration should be zero?  Acceleration is rate of change of velocity, and the direction of the velocity is changing.  So the acceleration is not zero and neither is the net force.</response>
            <answerformat>0</answerformat>
            <responseformat>0</responseformat>
